column14:
Couple of notes...

Firstly, it really frustrates me to see security vulnerabilities (however serious) to be publicly reported without even attempting to go the secure channels that Apache has in place. All vulnerabilities should be disclosed through https://www.apache.org/security/

Secondly, I'm not so sure if this is actually a security issue. `cordova-serve` is a development tool, so any process that access to this (or an attacker that can gain access to this) would already be able to execute commands without through to `cordova-serve`. See https://github.com/apache/cordova-serve/issues/36#issuecomment-649066476

Nonetheless, I still think it's a good idea to close behaviour that is obviously not intended. I've tested this fork locally and tests are passing.

This change should not be called a security fix, because we do not consider this to be a security vulnerability.

The name of the contributing developer or organization should not appear in the title.

The name of the actual human author, preferably with valid email address, should appear as the author in any commits that we would consider merging.

The proposal seems to be in multiple commits. Considering the relatively small size, I think we should consider merging in a single squash commit.

I think a title such as "avoid external code execution" would be much better.

column14:
Code looks great, nothing to say there (except there is some code redundancy, but not super important right now). Some larger issues around the feature itself:

* Removing the Bot/Not-Bot/Http-Code custom variables is a BC break. If existing users depend on them they will be forced to immediately move over to custom dimensions, which I think will be a problem. I think it would be better to have a parameter that switches from custom variables => custom dimensions.
  * Same for the --regex-group-to-...-cvar options. If someone's depending on them, this will cause problems for them.
* I haven't tested, but will this change result in errors if the CustomDimensions plugin is disabled? If so, that could cause problems for users.
* Looks like the code will always try and create a custom dimension for Http-Code/Bot/Not-Bot if one doesn't exist. I can't imagine everyone will want custom dimension slots taken up for those when there could be other more valuable (to them at least) dimensions they could be recording. This would also be an annoying surprise to someone who wasn't expecting it. I think this functionality should be off by default and enabled via CLI option.

üëç for the tests

CC @mattab / @tsteur (In fact, I wouldn't make changes based on these review comments until these two have weighed in.)

column14:
Nice. LGTM.

I don't think there's any particular way to make the numbers look 'nicer'. You could prevent the text from appearing horizontally squished by calculating the distortion that is being applied to the SVG, and then applying the inverse distortion to the text (i.e., the SVG is square by default but is forced into a rectangle by your CSS, this is what makes the text look squished).

LGTM

column14:
Wow, many thanks for adding a husky pre-commit hook and installing Prettier. ‚ú® This makes the project feel much cleaner and professional.

Unfortunately, this PR is a bit too big for me to seriously review it now (touches almost all blog posts and code files, and there are a few surprising changes mixed in like a new `yarn.lock`).

Could you please split up the work? (And maybe do that after some of your other PRs are merged, because otherwise you're going to make conflicting changes on the same files.)

E.g. maybe first install Prettier, and the pre-commit hook, without refactoring the entire codebase? Then, after that's merged, we can see about refactoring reasonable chunks of the codebase carefully while keeping PRs at reviewable size?

Agreed that there's value in this pull-request but too much was changed. Needs to be a smaller increment.

column14:
I was wondering how on earth cgimap wound up with an API extension relative to rails and it it turns out the history is far older and more baroque than I was expecting.

The cgimap version came in with https://github.com/zerebubuth/openstreetmap-cgimap/pull/129 which also added the single object versions calls which rails does have - that claims to be implementing #1189 for cgimap but actually is using a subtly different syntax.

That is probably a rather unfortunate syntax in fact because unlike #1189 it doesn't maintain the separation between main controller methods and history controller methods which then leads to the code here having to a complicated dance with the main controller accessing history objects and also to the non-deterministic uniqification where if you ask for the current version of an object in both versioned and unversioned form you don't know which one will be returned.

Now of course they should always be the same but it's an interesting wart.

I don't see any obvious problem with the code other than the rather complex nature of the abstract parent as @mmd-osm  noted which is not ideal but then equally neither is duplicating everything.

Possibly it would better to add new tests rather than add lots of cases to the existing ones. I suspect @gravitystorm will think so though he'd probably also say we should split the existing one.

Hi!

This is a very extensive change. Thanks for all the effort! I hope that my comments are helpful for you -- it's my first bigger review.

I think the functionality to trigger xAPI statements should not be included in youtube.js or html5.js unless it is absolutely necessary. video.js should be the central instance firing the statements regardless of the player used.

The players should just trigger an event (could be new ones) that can be caught by video.js, which in turn can collect all the necessary values and pass them to x-api.js just for firing the statements.

This way, some variable's that hold the state of the video (such as seeking) could be moved from x-api.js to video.js where they make more sense IMHO.

I have not yet had a detailed look at the conformity to the video CoP at https://github.com/liveaspankaj/xapi-video-cop/blob/master/statement_data_model.md. I also didn't check html5.js and youtube.js because of the comments above.

Some hints on styling:
- Please mark optional parameters as described in JSDoc, see http://usejsdoc.org/tags-param.html#optional-parameters-and-default-values.
- Please have check the indentation of the file. There are some debates about it, but I prefer to always use strict comparison such as !== instead of != (at least for consistency)
- Please use ' instead of " consistently.
- Don't forget semicolons.
Maybe https://h5p.org/documentation/for-developers/coding-guidelines could also be of support for you?

Best,
Oliver!

Hey everyone!

I think we're really close now. I think I found one bug that you should try to reproduce and take care of. Apart from that, the code seems to run nicely and do exactly what it should do. Good job!

Please consider the rest of my comments as suggestions. I mentioned some of them in my previous review, and I think the changes would improve the code,
but we're willing to do them ourselves. We do not want to upset you by our (probably quite, maybe too rigorous) review process. You've done a lot of work and we're really grateful. I think your contribution is a really cool contribution to both, H5P and xAPI.

column14:
I have pointed out some implementation issues mostly for educational purposes -- I think this is better approached differently.  If you look at `CreatePrimaryRequest::unlink_peer`, it already has logic for removing snapshots when `rbd_mirroring_max_mirroring_snapshots` limit is reached.  It also removes snapshots that aren't linked to any peer unconditionally (i.e. even if `rbd_mirroring_max_mirroring_snapshots` limit isn't reached).  It seems like we could piggy-back on that just by adding an extra provision for incomplete snapshots.

It may not be apparent that `CreatePrimaryRequest::unlink_peer` can remove snapshots because it invokes a fairly nondescript `UnlinkPeerRequest` to do the work, but `UnlinkPeerRequest` actually ends up calling `snap_remove` if certain conditions are met.  I suspect that an incomplete snapshot would meet those conditions.

Did you verify that `UnlinkPeerRequest` would actually remove the snapshot in this case?

Also please squash the test commit and drop the BZ link.

I completed the review.

General findings for tests:

* Check the test names. Make them [PEP8](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#function-and-variable-names) compliant. By example: `test_AWSBucket_already_processed` to `test_aws_bucket_already_processed`.
* Use more descriptive names following the GIVEN-WHEN-THEN or SHOULD-WHEN conventions. By example `test_AWSBucket_create_table_ko` to `test_create_table_didnt_raise_when_table_cannot_be_created`.
* Also avoid unit test private methods. Instead, test them through the public interface.
* Use `os.path.join` for build paths. By example in: `f'AWSLogs/{utils.TEST_ACCOUNT_ID}/Config/{utils.TEST_REGION}/{custom_date.strftime(instance.date_format)}'` -> `os.path.join('AWSLogs', utils.TEST_ACCOUNT_ID, 'Config', utils.TEST_REGION, custom_date.strftime(instance.date_format))`

LGTM

Good to me üëç 

From the past experience with similar stats on other detail pages (email, campaign, ...) data like this will cause troubles:
1. The count query is very time consuming when the table size goes to millions and more. We are optimizing count queries that take minutes for our clients. Meaning that if we merge this I see a priority ticket following right after saying that some focus item pages are loading way to slow or timing out. How to solve this? Caching and/or loading it asynchronously.
2. The number of hits can be higher than number of focus stats. So the conversion rate will be confusing to users. Imagine that you view the focus item once and click the link twice. Which will result in more support tickets. How about to use `unique_hits` instead of `hits`?
3. It will be also confusing for users whether the conversion rate shows numbers for the selected time period or total.
4. Why the 4 decimal number rounding? I think that 1 would be enough. 2 max.

Tested, found some issues:

1. In case where 3 contacts viewed the page with Focus item, one of them twice:

![image](https://github.com/mautic/mautic/assets/130159751/bea085d8-c307-4781-8a40-e3bbffa1912f)
Two of those contacts clicked on links:
![image](https://github.com/mautic/mautic/assets/130159751/496cc25f-8898-4c38-8e89-05e068c5ff6e)
The total Conversion Rate should be 2/3=66.6%, since we should take unique views (3, not 4 in this case)

2. In the tooltip for Total conversion rate the description should be written the other way around: 
Number of contacts that clicked on at least one link/Total views

3. Views in the table are not refreshed immediately with the rest of the data:

- Cached data timeout in System settings is bigger than 0
- One contact clicks on all of the links
- Wait for the data to be refreshed (views too)
- Second contact clicks on all of the links 
- Views is still 1, the rest of the data is updated immediately.
- While we wait for views to refresh Conversion rate for the links is 200%:
![image](https://github.com/mautic/mautic/assets/130159751/9c4604a2-1ae5-4c11-aeae-ec15c3a5c845)



@patrykgruszka retests done, everything works
![image](https://github.com/mautic/mautic/assets/130159751/037c092f-6306-4409-bfaf-47426b4f755b)

While reviewing this PR I noticed that we have a separate [`firewall-bypass`](https://cloudcustodian.io/docs/azure/resources/sql-server.html#azure-sql-server-filters-firewall-bypass) filter that _seems_ to cover this case.

The [`firewall-rules` docs](https://cloudcustodian.io/docs/azure/resources/azure-common-filters.html#azure-common-filters-firewall-rules) have a note about that:

> IMPORTANT: this filter ignores all bypass rules. If you want to ensure your resource is not available for other Azure Cloud services or from the Portal, please use `firewall-bypass` filter.

That said, it looks like the `firewall-bypass` filter isn't available for Postgres. _If_ this actually covers what it looks like, then perhaps we can pivot to adding a Postgres `firewall-bypass` filter and using the existing one for sqlserver.

lgtm, thanks

Good work, almost there!

Also we need to do the following changes:

- Remove all the settings that we move to DB from the `settings.py`
- We need to change `shuup_init` management command to set the default values when it is ran. I think we can create a signal that we can trigger inside it so all apps can listed to it and ensure their initial settings, like this:

1) Create a signal `shuup_inited` inside `shuup/core/signals.py`.
2) Inside `shuup/core/management/commands/shuup_init.py`, before `set_current_theme` call you trigger it: `shuup_inited.send(sender=type(self))`

3) Move the `set_current_theme` to `shuup/xtheme/signal_handlers.py`:
```py
@receiver(shuup_inited)
def on_shuup_inited(sender, **kwargs):
    set_current_theme("shuup.themes.classic_gray", Shop.objects.first())
```

4) Let's ensure the default settings for core, front and reports in their respective signal_handlers.py:

in core:
```
@receiver(shuup_inited)
def on_shuup_inited(sender, **kwargs):
    configuration.set(None, SHUUP_HOME_CURRENCY, "EUR")
    configuration.set(None, SHUUP_ALLOW_ANONYMOUS_ORDERS, True)
    ... all other settings
```

the same with front and reports. This is to make sure NEW installations have the settings we expect them to have without breaking things.

Great job!

All your tests are passing and your code is very readable.

One main thing I'd focus on going forward is identifying repetitive parts of the code and moving them to helper methods or class instance methods. We can create our own additional classes to help us organize common code and represent reusable ideas. Especially for CRUD models, there is a lot of very similar code. Even if it's not exactly the same, thinking about how to move that similar code into shared routines can help up organize and test our code. Our testing in this project focused on testing through the flask client helper, but we can write smaller unit tests similar to the tests we used in Video Party and Swap Meet, which are easier to write when the logic is pulled out into small units of code that focus on single responsibilities.

Specifically with respect to writing web apis with Flask and SqlAlchemy, keep looking at other examples and looking through the documentation for other ideas about helper methods and implementation patterns. Using decorator methods can also be a useful strategy for common tasks if we split our routes into separate methods.

Overall, you did really well, and the rest will come with continued practice and experimentation. Keep it up!!! üéâ

column14:
:+1: This change seems straightforward, nice work

I have pointed out some methods that now require the new Exception parameter as they don't specify a default value, and I believe this would cause a breaking change.

I'm also going to point out this [somewhat related blog post](https://haacked.com/archive/2010/08/10/versioning-issues-with-optional-arguments.aspx/) around being careful when using optional parameters. It suggests that adding optional parameters to an existing method can cause runtime exceptions if an application has not been compiled, but has a new version of a client library that has added optional parameters to existing methods. I would expect applications to typically be compiled when upgrading to newer versions of client libraries though, so maybe it's not a concern for us.

column14:
We discussed this in person at the Karlsruhe Hack Weekend, so this is only a summary of that review. Namely:

* We can rework the default handling in opengraph_tags to use a more conventional ruby approach of using `tags = {}` in the method signature, and `tags.reverse_merge(defaults)`
* However, we need to rethink how the function handles the title. It's a specific parameter at the moment, but it makes sense to combine that with other overrides somehow
* You're going to add the user profile image too, which is important because that uses a view helper, and those aren't normally available in controllers. Although we can bodge that in (by using `helpers` in the controller) it's an indication that we're mixing up the separation of concerns between controllers and views
* For the body, we need to check whether implementations handle "og:description" as html, or whether we need to pass only textual content to that
* entry.body will return raw markup, whether html or markdown, and we probably don't want that in the description
* We need some tests for the three different diary entry body types
* We need some rational for why 100 characters, and not e.g. 200 
* Is there a better way to truncate the text, rather than just characters. I couldn't find an example in the codebase but perhaps there is either a rails helper or something similar to intelligently truncate. 
* We need some other tests just to make sure that the type, title etc is what we expect so that it survives future refactoring.
